{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510303"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:27:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:27:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11515"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11515"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.31,0.02,0.02,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4146"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88450"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4146"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11515"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72651"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1504"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5218"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15073"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15132"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30231"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88450"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-day history of progressively worsening abdominal pain. He recently spent two weeks in hospital being treated for community-acquired pneumonia and was discharged one week ago. He reports not having opened his bowels for the past five days, despite being on regular macrogol and coloxyl with senna. His last bowel movement was watery and loose and did not contain any blood. He is mildly nauseated but has not vomited. He has lost approximately 1-2 kg since his recent admission due to poor appetite, and is currently on a soft puree diet.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and chronic kidney disease. His regular medications are perindopril, metformin, insulin, inhaled salbutamol, and ipratropium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable but otherwise well. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a distended abdomen and palpable masses in the lower abdomen consistent with stools. Bowel sounds are present. Digital rectal examination reveals a loaded rectum with firm stools. An abdominal x-ray shows faecal loading throughout the large bowel.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sodium phosphate enema","Manual faecal disimpaction","High fibre diet","Exploratory laparotomy","Standard bowel preparation (polyethylene glycol)"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with generalised abdominal pain and distention, palpable masses in the lower abdomen consistent with stools, and hard stools on digital rectal examination. This is consistent with faecal impaction of the lower gastrointestinal tract, commonly seen in older patients with a lack of mobilisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStandard bowel preparation (polyethylene glycol)\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. These are electrolyte-containing solutions that provide a simple, safe, gentle and effective treatment for faecal impaction. These preparations have an osmotic effect and draw water into the intestinal lumen to loosen stools. Most come in an oral sachet and are easy for older patients to consume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium phosphate enema\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered as an alternative treatment, but is not generally recommended in the elderly or those with significant renal disease due to a risk of severe electrolyte imbalances and volume depletion. It will also not be as effective for impaction higher up in the colon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EManual faecal disimpaction\u003C/strong\u003E involves manually removing fragmented pieces of faeces within the rectum using a finger. This procedure can be used to alleviate constipation if pharmacological remedies fail to work. However, it is more invasive and can cause significant pain and discomfort. Some form of sedation/anaesthesia is often required and that could be problematic in an older, unfit patient, such as described here. Standard bowel preparation would be the more appropriate and simple next step in management before manual faecal disimpaction is considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh fibre diet\u003C/strong\u003E can be utilised to encourage bowel activity in the longer term, but it is not appropriate in this context given the severity of his constipation and his poor oral intake. It may take weeks to take effect and could potentially worsen the impaction if there is not enough fluid intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExploratory laparotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely indicated in older patients with constipation unless there are complications such as bowel ischaemia or perforation. In this case, there are no signs of such severe complications, making surgery an unnecessarily invasive option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, standard bowel preparation with polyethylene glycol offers the best balance of effectiveness and safety for this patient\u0027s faecal impaction. If this fails, more invasive options like manual disimpaction could be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Standard bowel preparation is a simple, useful initial management in older patients with faecal impaction.","Faecal impaction commonly presents with generalised abdominal pain, distention, and palpable masses in the lower abdomen consistent with stools.","Manual faecal disimpaction and surgery are more invasive options reserved for cases refractory to pharmacological management."],"references":["Brandt LJ, Prather CM, Quigley EM, Schiller LR, Schoenfeld P, Talley NJ. Systematic review on the management of chronic constipation in North America. Am J Gastroenterol. 2005;100 Suppl 1:S5-S21. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16008641/","Rao SS, Rattanakovit K, Patcharatrakul T. Diagnosis and management of chronic constipation in adults. Nat Rev Gastroenterol Hepatol 2016; 13:295. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27033126/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72651"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11515"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72651"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-04T14:42:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-04T14:44:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4146"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88450"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":